  "description": "Programmability is a concept developed by Wendy Chun in Programmed Visions: Software and Memory (2011) [cite:@chun_ProgrammedVisions_2011] and Updating to Remain the Same: Habitual New Media (2016) [cite:@chun_UpdatingRemainSame_2016]. It describes a mode of governance in which responsiveness is simulated but not real — the platform speaks as if present but is structurally absent. Control operates not through direct command but through the containment of timing failure.\nChun argues that digital platforms do not respond to events as such. They respond to the breakdown of synchronization — the moment when expected timing patterns fail to hold. A platform\u0026rsquo;s apparent responsiveness masks a deeper operation: the continuous re-establishment of temporal alignment between user behavior and system expectations. When that alignment breaks, the platform does not deliberate; it executes pre-structured routines that restore synchronization or reroute the failure.\n",
  "name": "Programmability",
